=====Linux Introduction=====
Linux is an open-source operating system (OS).
It was created by Linus Torvalds in 1991.
Linux is based on Unix concepts and design.
It is free to use, modify, and distribute.
Linux is known for stability, security, and performance.
It is widely used in servers, cloud computing, DevOps, and cybersecurity.
Most websites on the Internet run on Linux servers.
Cloud platforms like AWS, Azure, and Google Cloud heavily use Linux.
Docker and Kubernetes are primarily designed to run on Linux.
Linux supports multiple users at the same time (Multi-user OS).
It can run multiple programs simultaneously (Multitasking OS).
Linux works on desktops, laptops, servers, mobile devices, and embedded systems.
Android is built on the Linux kernel.
Linux has a Command Line Interface (CLI) and a Graphical User Interface (GUI).
The command line is called the Terminal or Shell.
Linux stores everything as files, including devices.
Linux uses a hierarchical directory structure starting from the root (/).
Linux has powerful file permissions for security.
Linux is highly customizable according to user needs.
Linux has many distributions (distros) such as Ubuntu, CentOS, Debian, Fedora, Rocky Linux, AlmaLinux, and Kali Linux.
Software in Linux is managed using package managers like apt, yum, dnf, and zypper.
Linux is case-sensitive (File.txt and file.txt are different files).
Linux provides excellent networking capabilities.
It is preferred for automation using Shell Scripting.
Most DevOps tools such as Git, Jenkins, Docker, Ansible, Terraform, Kubernetes, and Prometheus are commonly used on Linux.
Linux is considered one of the most reliable operating systems for production environments.
Many supercomputers run Linux because of its performance and flexibility.
Linux has a large global community that contributes to its development.
Learning Linux is one of the most important skills for DevOps Engineers, Cloud Engineers, Site Reliability Engineers (SREs), and System Administrators.


Simple Definition
------------------------

Linux is a free, open-source operating system that manages computer hardware and software resources, allowing users and applications to communicate with the computer efficiently.

Real-World Example
------------------------------
Imagine a company like Amazon.

Employees access a website.
The website is hosted on Linux servers.
Docker containers run on Linux.
Kubernetes manages those containers on Linux.
AWS EC2 instances often use Linux.
Jenkins pipelines execute on Linux.
Web servers like Apache and Nginx run on Linux.
Without Linux, most modern cloud infrastructure would not function as it does today.

Why Learn Linux for DevOps?
------------------------------------

AWS EC2 mostly uses Linux.
Docker is built around Linux features.
Kubernetes worker nodes commonly run Linux.
Jenkins agents often run on Linux.
Ansible primarily manages Linux servers.
Terraform provisions Linux infrastructure.
Shell scripting is based on Linux commands.
Nearly every DevOps interview includes Linux questions.

